      <li id="sl_n">
        <p>World of Warcraft</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="RB">
            <p>World of Warcraft Classic is an example of really good product design.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="RW">
            <p>I never considered this before, but that game was such a joy to play,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4ZTE">
            <p>and this is evident by the number of players who returned to try the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wN">
            <p>Classic re-release.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7O">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="jCo5">
        <p>A Pattern Language</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="sBtN">
            <p>A possibly interesting read that I've heard about in several places.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="Kpy-">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="bcHo">
        <p>Electricity and literacy</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="R0">
            <p>Electricity made possible, the technology that sidestep literacy and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="AA">
            <p>allowed politicians to speak directly to the masses 80 years ago.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dF">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="Rllh">
        <p>Jobs on making money</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="2J">
            <p>“The goal was never to beat the competition, or to make a lot of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jJ">
            <p>money. It was to do the greatest thing possible or even a little</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pL">
            <p>greater”</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Us">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="sA">
            <p>Steve Jobs &amp;#x2013; Hertzfield.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="86nd">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="3tLz">
        <p>Bauhaus</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="AX3-">
            <p>Alright, imagine you're a kid and you have a big box of building</p>
          </li>
          <li id="EY">
            <p>blocks. Some blocks are red, some are blue, and some are yellow. Now,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2v">
            <p>instead of building fancy and ornate castles with intricate designs,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="qi">
            <p>you decide to make simple, functional structures with clean lines and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8i">
            <p>primary colors. You believe that these simple structures, even though</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tD">
            <p>they're not fancy, are beautiful in their own way because of their</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4DDJ">
            <p>simplicity, function, and the basic colors you're using.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cl">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="vg">
            <p>This idea of simple, functional, and clean design is a lot like the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="conR">
            <p>Bauhaus movement.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="JV">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="DiHq">
            <p>Back in the day, around the 1920s in Germany, a school called the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8yo7">
            <p>Bauhaus was founded. This school believed that art, crafts, and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="v3rU">
            <p>technology should come together to create functional and simple</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Hx">
            <p>designs. They thought that objects, even everyday ones like chairs or</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Pn">
            <p>teapots, should be both useful and beautiful in a simple way.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="kC">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="xn">
            <p>Instead of adding lots of decoration and details to objects and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nGxZ">
            <p>buildings, Bauhaus designers kept things straightforward and focused</p>
          </li>
          <li id="19">
            <p>on the basic forms and functions. They also loved using primary</p>
          </li>
          <li id="io">
            <p>colors, just like your building blocks.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9R">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ci0V">
            <p>So, in short, the Bauhaus movement was all about simplicity,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cBUr">
            <p>functionality, and bringing different arts together to make everyday</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ZhnA">
            <p>things beautiful in their own unique way.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Tu">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="gY2h">
            <p>TODO: buy the book</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Br">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="iI84">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="35aa">
        <p>Even what is hidden should remain beautiful</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="7OlE">
            <p>“I want it to be as beautiful as possible, even if it’s inside the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Dr">
            <p>box. A great carpenter isn’t going to use lousy wood for the back of a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aS">
            <p>cabinet, even though nobody’s going to see it”</p>
          </li>
          <li id="It">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="oTdw">
            <p>Steve Jobs</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="IEc7">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="-Qgm">
        <p>The Journey is the reward</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="OpAv">
            <p>“The journey is the reward.” The Mac team, he liked to emphasise was a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="e4">
            <p>special corps with an exalted mission. Someday they would all look</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aB">
            <p>back on their journey together and forgetting or laughing off the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sIBs">
            <p>painful moments would regard it as a magical high point in their lives</p>
          </li>
          <li id="m3">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="-I">
            <p>Steve Jobs</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="7K-3">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="izYn">
        <p>B and C Players</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="oIzd">
            <p>“It’s too easy as a team grows to put up with a few B players, and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B9vD">
            <p>they then attract a few more B players and soon you will even have</p>
          </li>
          <li id="6Q">
            <p>some C players”</p>
          </li>
          <li id="eT">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="QFRW">
            <p>Jobs</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="WHoZ">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="tb8J">
        <p>Twitter makes you feel depressed as shit</p>
      </li>
      <li id="k0mJ">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="KXa4">
        <p>Car allergic to vanilla ice cream</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="MZ">
            <p>&lt;http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~wkw/humour/carproblems.txt&gt;</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wc">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="sdRr">
        <p>Impute from first values</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="sSJi">
            <p>A great company must be able to impute its values from the first</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B_j_">
            <p>impression it makes</p>
          </li>
          <li id="IM">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="bI">
            <p>Jobs</p>
          </li>
          <li id="qHUr">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="Zj">
        <p>Great Harvests come from Arid sources</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="S5q_">
            <p>“He believed that great harvests came from arid sources, pleasure from</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Gf">
            <p>restraint. He knew the equations that most people didn’t know: Things</p>
          </li>
          <li id="J2">
            <p>led to their opposites.”</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Vf">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="IY">
            <p>Jobs</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="st0i">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="BPqw">
        <p>Crazy people</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="iRqv">
            <p>Because the people who are crazy enough to think they can change the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fN">
            <p>world are the ones who do</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Bn">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="8I">
            <p>Jobs</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="m0EJ">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="_6_Q">
        <p>Ives and Rams</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="pg16">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="If">
            <p>Ive was a fan of the German industrial designer Dieter Rams, who</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vb">
            <p>worked for the electronics firm Braun. Rams preached the gospel of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="CVHC">
            <p>“Less but better”, Weniger aber besser, and likewise Jobs and Ive</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tm">
            <p>wrestled with each new design to see how much they could simplify it.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="1N">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="1p4t">
            <p>Jobs Book</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="Qr87">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="ApoF">
        <p>Why is Simple good?</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="LRJ2">
            <p>Why do we assume that simple is good? Because with physical products,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zD">
            <p>we have to feel we can dominate them. As you bring order to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="p_">
            <p>complexity, you find a way to make the product defer to you.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nR">
            <p>Simplicity isn’t just a visual style. It’s not just minimalism or the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="korh">
            <p>absence of clutter. It involves digging through the depth of the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YO">
            <p>complexity. To be truly simple, you have to go really deep.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="UK">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Zg">
            <p>Jobs</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dTg1">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="HaJ9">
        <p>Ive and Jobs, knife</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="AsAf">
            <p>Ive picked up a knife he admired, but then put it down in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4Gc4">
            <p>disappointment. Jobs did the same. “We both noticed a tiny bit of glue</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hZ">
            <p>between the handle and the blade”, Ive recalled. They talked about how</p>
          </li>
          <li id="r1hn">
            <p>how the knife’s hold design had been ruined by the way it was</p>
          </li>
          <li id="QR">
            <p>manufactured. “We don’t like to think of our knives as being glued</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pJsT">
            <p>together”, Ive said. “Steve and I care about things like that, which</p>
          </li>
          <li id="eV">
            <p>ruin the purity and detract from the essence of something like a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="goaz">
            <p>toenail, and we think alike about how products should be made to look</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mbqi">
            <p>pure and seamless”</p>
          </li>
          <li id="38">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="To">
            <p>Steve Jobs Book</p>
          </li>
          <li id="c5Mv">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="1qFT">
        <p>Mind Pollution</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="MdxD">
            <p>I really do believe there is this idea that your mind can be polluted</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tV">
            <p>by the bullshit around you. You should actively seek to purge it and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="P9">
            <p>block it from your life. E.g. most mainstream adverts aimed at boring</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pa">
            <p>and worthless laypeople, or TikTok videos.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="c8P4">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="DVmh">
        <p>To All Conspiracy Theorists</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="oYM1">
            <p>To all conspiracy theorists: I took a 5 year degree in computing. When</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3l">
            <p>I finished my degree, I had more questions than when I started. I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S8">
            <p>encourage you to do the same, and then you will realise that it is an</p>
          </li>
          <li id="slYu">
            <p>impossible task to take a hardline stance on anything, especially in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="yc">
            <p>such a short window of time as a day, or a week.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="XEIG">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="uHQm">
        <p>Notes from call with Prot</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="hu">
            <p>Hombrew package: ISync</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aH">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="7W">
            <p>Executeable: mbsync</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3sSt">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="lC">
            <p>MMM package</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Hh">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="d2_3">
            <p>`Package-vc-install`</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jW">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="n5">
            <p>Use the following:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="uA">
            <p>`modus-themes-mixed-fonts t`</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jT">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="sy">
                <p>;; NOTE 2022-11-20: This may not cover every case, though it works</p>
              </li>
              <li id="mN">
                <p>;; fine in my workflow.  I am still undecided by EWW.</p>
              </li>
              <li id="1q">
                <p>(defun prot/enable-variable-pitch ()</p>
              </li>
              <li id="tZ">
                <p>(unless (or (derived-mode-p 'mhtml-mode 'nxml-mode 'yaml-mode)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li id="Ua">
                    <p>(member (buffer-name) '("*Colors*" "*Faces*" "*Quick Help*")))</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="JL">
                    <p>(variable-pitch-mode 1)))</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="ZC">
                    <p/>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li id="hd">
                <p>(defvar prot/enable-variable-pitch-in-hooks</p>
              </li>
              <li id="M4">
                <p>'(text-mode-hook</p>
                <ul>
                  <li id="EsMm">
                    <p>help-mode-hook</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="V4mX">
                    <p>notmuch-show-mode-hook</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="z2">
                    <p>elfeed-show-mode-hook)</p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li id="0L">
                <p>"List of hook symbols to add `prot/enable-variable-pitch' to.")</p>
              </li>
              <li id="W5">
                <p/>
              </li>
              <li id="LD">
                <p>(dolist (hook prot/enable-variable-pitch-in-hooks)</p>
              </li>
              <li id="wv">
                <p>(add-hook hook #'prot/enable-variable-pitch))</p>
              </li>
              <li id="Zp">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Hj">
            <p>`text-mode-hook` also works for org-mode</p>
          </li>
          <li id="W5Gm">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="dYLW">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="HeAH">
        <p>Suckless software principles</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="7X">
            <p>Philosophy</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0V">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="z_">
            <p>We are the home of quality software such as dwm, dmenu, st and plenty</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dU">
            <p>of other tools, with a focus on simplicity, clarity and frugality. Our</p>
          </li>
          <li id="UP">
            <p>philosophy is about keeping things simple, minimal and usable. We</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jA">
            <p>believe this should become the mainstream philosophy in the IT</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-V">
            <p>sector. Unfortunately, the tendency for complex, error-prone and slow</p>
          </li>
          <li id="A4">
            <p>software seems to be prevalent in the present-day software</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ns">
            <p>industry. We intend to prove the opposite with our software projects.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="6a">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_p">
            <p>Our project focuses on advanced and experienced computer users. In</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ox">
            <p>contrast with the usual proprietary software world or many mainstream</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sFG0">
            <p>open source projects that focus more on average and non-technical end</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Vi">
            <p>users, we think that experienced users are mostly ignored. This is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7a">
            <p>particularly true for user interfaces, such as graphical environments</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WL">
            <p>on desktop computer, on mobile devices, and in so-called Web</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xP">
            <p>applications. We believe that the market of experienced users is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xV">
            <p>growing continuously, with each user looking for more appropriate</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7n">
            <p>solutions for his/her work style.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="HA">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="W6">
            <p>Designing simple and elegant software is far more difficult than</p>
          </li>
          <li id="bQ">
            <p>letting ad-hoc or over-ambitious features obscure the code over</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Er">
            <p>time. However one has to pay this price to achieve reliability and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="NM">
            <p>maintainability. Furthermore, minimalism results in reasonable and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zZ">
            <p>attainable goals. We strive to maintain minimalism and clarity to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="IZ">
            <p>drive development to completion.  Manifest</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ag">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="iL">
            <p>Many (open source) hackers are proud if they achieve large amounts of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="NJXE">
            <p>code, because they believe the more lines of code they've written, the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="G_">
            <p>more progress they have made. The more progress they have made, the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="E8">
            <p>more skilled they are. This is simply a delusion.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Q5">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="G8">
            <p>Most hackers actually don't care much about code quality. Thus, if</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Rd">
            <p>they get something working which seems to solve a problem, they stick</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ov">
            <p>with it. If this kind of software development is applied to the same</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SI">
            <p>source code throughout its entire life-cycle, we're left with large</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Cx">
            <p>amounts of code, a totally screwed code structure, and a flawed system</p>
          </li>
          <li id="t8">
            <p>design. This is because of a lack of conceptual clarity and integrity</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sY">
            <p>in the development process.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3x">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="uZ">
            <p>Code complexity is the mother of bloated, hard to use, and totally</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Si">
            <p>inconsistent software. With complex code, problems are solved in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_Z">
            <p>suboptimal ways, valuable resources are endlessly tied up, performance</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ak">
            <p>slows to a halt, and vulnerabilities become a commonplace. The only</p>
          </li>
          <li id="QD">
            <p>solution is to scrap the entire project and rewrite it from scratch.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="FE">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="qG">
            <p>The bad news: quality rewrites rarely happen, because hackers are</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nU">
            <p>proud of large amounts of code. They think they understand the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hK">
            <p>complexity in the code, thus there's no need to rewrite it. They think</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Gv">
            <p>of themselves as masterminds, understanding what others can never hope</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8s">
            <p>to grasp. To these types, complex software is the ideal.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BE8">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Squ">
            <p>Ingenious ideas are simple. Ingenious software is simple. Simplicity</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Jxt">
            <p>is the heart of the Unix philosophy. The more code lines you have</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0Xb">
            <p>removed, the more progress you have made. As the number of lines of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5qf">
            <p>code in your software shrinks, the more skilled you have become and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="UYZ">
            <p>the less your software sucks.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-9N">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="qgg">
            <p>&lt;https://suckless.org/philosophy/&gt;</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wTYG">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="amdI">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="ggQy">
        <p>Ghibli wallpaper collection</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="KX">
            <p>&lt;https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1MPECo6qYJejKuYdIot6EgvfINvAPnTGv&gt;</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="YXH_">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="jCCT">
        <p>Visual design rules you can safely follow</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="rrc0">
            <p>&lt;https://anthonyhobday.com/sideprojects/saferules/&gt;</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GH">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="69">
            <p>Visual design rules you can safely follow every time</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mx">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Oy">
            <p>You do not have to follow these rules every time. If you have a good</p>
          </li>
          <li id="LR">
            <p>reason to break any of them, do. But they are safe to follow every</p>
          </li>
          <li id="s3">
            <p>time.  Use near-black and near-white instead of pure black and white</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wG">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="4K">
            <p>Pure black looks unnatural on a screen, and pure white is too</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KT">
            <p>bright. Use close-to-black and close-to-white instead. Any other</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mr">
            <p>references to “black” and “white” in these rules assume you’re</p>
          </li>
          <li id="eL5B">
            <p>following this rule.  Saturate your neutrals</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Dq">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Nx">
            <p>A neutral is generally a black, white, or grey. If you use colour in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sR">
            <p>your interface, add a little bit of that colour to your neutrals. This</p>
          </li>
          <li id="W-">
            <p>will make the colour palette feel more coherent. If you use the HSB</p>
          </li>
          <li id="e1">
            <p>colour system less than 5% saturation should do it.  Use high contrast</p>
          </li>
          <li id="eOKf">
            <p>for important elements</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Qx">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="V_">
            <p>Important elements means buttons, content, or anything else that the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="FX">
            <p>user needs to notice. A higher contrast means that the element will</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Qm">
            <p>grab attention, which is useful for important elements. Elements that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Bd">
            <p>the user does not need to notice (e.g. structural elements,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="b_">
            <p>drop-shadows) can use as little contrast as possible.  Everything in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wk">
            <p>your design should be deliberate</p>
          </li>
          <li id="XJ">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="uv">
            <p>You should be deliberate about absolutely everything in your</p>
          </li>
          <li id="HR">
            <p>design. This means whitespace, alignment, size, spacing, colour,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="K4">
            <p>shadows. Everything. If someone points at a random part of your design</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WX">
            <p>you should have an explanation for why it looks that way. If you do</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tQ">
            <p>not do this your design will not feel coherent.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Oi">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="RF">
            <p>If you are new to design you can use this rule as a prompt to learn</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Qo">
            <p>more about what you are not deliberate about yet.  Optical alignment</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-a">
            <p>is often better than mathematical alignment</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ds">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="78">
            <p>Your design software can align things mathematically. But some shapes</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Eb">
            <p>don’t suit this type of alignment. For example, some odd shapes have a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="gz">
            <p>visual centre that is different from their mathematical centre. Often</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BT">
            <p>you will need to align things by eye so that it looks right.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="C-">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="fH">
            <p>It takes some practice to be able to align things by eye, but if you</p>
          </li>
          <li id="um">
            <p>do it regularly you’ll quickly pick it up.  Lower letter spacing and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="LH">
            <p>line height with larger text. Raise them with smaller text</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Gk">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="D-">
            <p>This applies to all text. The bigger the text, the less space you need</p>
          </li>
          <li id="u1">
            <p>between each letter and each line. The reverse is also true. If you do</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Dy">
            <p>not do this large text can look spread out, and small text can look</p>
          </li>
          <li id="A8">
            <p>too close.  Container borders should contrast with both the container</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hq">
            <p>and the background</p>
          </li>
          <li id="V5">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="24">
            <p>Example: If you have a card with a 1px border and a dark background,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="rk">
            <p>and it sits on top of an even darker background, the 1px border should</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WO">
            <p>be lighter than both of them. It should not be set to a brightness</p>
          </li>
          <li id="e9">
            <p>somewhere between the card and page background colours. Otherwise the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="1Y">
            <p>edge of the container won’t look sharp enough. The same applies to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wF">
            <p>light background colours: the 1px border should be darker than both</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pT">
            <p>background colours.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ji">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Xj">
            <p>In the example below the left side is incorrect and the right side is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="QxIp">
            <p>correct.  Everything should be aligned with something else</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zn">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="emE0">
            <p>Alignment helps us realise that things are related to each other. If</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8h">
            <p>something is not aligned with anything else, it feels like it does not</p>
          </li>
          <li id="iM">
            <p>belong in the design. Ideally each element should be aligned with</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4ZHU">
            <p>other elements based on some kind of logic.  Colours in a palette</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7y">
            <p>should have distinct brightness values</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Uu">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_I">
            <p>When colours have different brightness values, this helps them look</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mi">
            <p>and feel distinctive not just in hue, but in brightness. This leads to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fl">
            <p>better colour palettes because colours don’t compete with each other</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ys">
            <p>as much.  If you saturate your neutrals you should use warm or cool</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mr">
            <p>colours, not both</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Lh">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="neB">
            <p>If you use both warm and cool colours to saturate neutrals, the colour</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5ij">
            <p>palette will not feel coherent.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="a-W">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="tf7">
            <p>In the example below the left side uses a warm background and a cool</p>
          </li>
          <li id="1MS">
            <p>foreground. The right side uses a warm background and foreground.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="NAK">
            <p>Measurements should be mathematically related</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Hzz">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="iMY">
            <p>The spacing you use between elements, and the size of elements, should</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GEx">
            <p>be determined by some kind of scale. This will help the design to look</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Nd3">
            <p>coherent. In the example below, every element uses multiples</p>
          </li>
          <li id="e4i">
            <p>of 8. Horizontal and vertical grids based on a scale help if you want</p>
          </li>
          <li id="p8k">
            <p>to make sure elements like pictures are the right size.  Elements</p>
          </li>
          <li id="TQL">
            <p>should go in order of visual weight</p>
          </li>
          <li id="69_">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="B6A">
            <p>If you have a series of elements in a row or column, and some are more</p>
          </li>
          <li id="PlD">
            <p>visually heavy than others (two buttons and three links, for example),</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ZZW">
            <p>you should arrange them like a triangle. The visually heaviest element</p>
          </li>
          <li id="MZ9">
            <p>should go first, and the least heavy element last, in order. One</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oUc">
            <p>caveat is that the visually heaviest element should be on the outside</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wBi">
            <p>edge. If your elements are against the right edge of the design, for</p>
          </li>
          <li id="G-B">
            <p>example, the heaviest element should be against the right</p>
          </li>
          <li id="USr">
            <p>edge. Elements that go in size or weight order look more satisfying.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="MyG">
            <p>If you use a horizontal grid, use 12 columns</p>
          </li>
          <li id="EhO">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_aN">
            <p>If you’re going to break your design up into vertical columns, use 12</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Brv">
            <p>columns. A 12 column grid can be broken up into 1 column, 2 columns, 3</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Klr">
            <p>columns, and 4 columns, so it gives you a lot of flexibility.  Spacing</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4x5">
            <p>should go between points of high contrast</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WRn">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="lTf">
            <p>When you’re measuring out space between elements in a design—for</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_Qf">
            <p>example if you want 100px of vertical space between blocks of content</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2BX">
            <p>on a landing page—the spacing should be from one point of high</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B60">
            <p>contrast to the next. This is because our eyes find the edges of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="irv">
            <p>elements based on contrast, so we expect the spacing to run between</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YrR">
            <p>points of contrast.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Cfg">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="s0E">
            <p>A white background with black paragraphs of text means that the points</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lrt">
            <p>of contrast will be the end of one paragraph and the start of the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Z-T">
            <p>next. But if you put a black background behind one white paragraph,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xyA">
            <p>the spacing should run from the end of one paragraph to the start of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="scS">
            <p>the black background, then again from the start of the black</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Sgq">
            <p>background to the start of the paragraph.  Closer elements should be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ouW">
            <p>lighter</p>
          </li>
          <li id="D3N">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="7fo">
            <p>As elements on the screen get closer to the user, they should get</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BXM">
            <p>lighter. This applies to both light and dark mode UIs, because it</p>
          </li>
          <li id="L1n">
            <p>matches how the real world works.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="po_">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="wVk">
            <p>In the example below, the left side is incorrect and the right side is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OM2">
            <p>correct.  Make drop shadow blur values double their distance values</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Iwp">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Va9">
            <p>e.g. If you create a shadow which extends 4 pixels on the Y axis, use</p>
          </li>
          <li id="DZJ">
            <p>a blur value of 8 pixels. As the element gets “closer” to the viewer,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="DFW">
            <p>it’s a good idea to also lower the opacity of the shadow. This looks</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-_n">
            <p>good because as elements move closer to the light source, their</p>
          </li>
          <li id="m1W">
            <p>shadows get more blurry.  Put simple on complex or complex on simple</p>
          </li>
          <li id="z5b">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="SrO">
            <p>A complex background (e.g. a colourful gradient fill) works best if</p>
          </li>
          <li id="34a">
            <p>the foreground (e.g. text) is simple. And a complex foreground element</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5RK">
            <p>is best on a simple background. You can put simple on simple, but it</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mNA">
            <p>tends to look plain. Complex on complex should be avoided because it’s</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2nI">
            <p>hard to pull off and will add visual clutter.  Keep container colours</p>
          </li>
          <li id="EN3">
            <p>within brightness limits</p>
          </li>
          <li id="r3R">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="RwV">
            <p>The brightness difference between background and container should be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="U1k">
            <p>within 12% for dark interfaces, and 7% for light interfaces. These</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nNp">
            <p>percentages refer to the brightness value in the HSB colour system.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wbd">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="nL0">
            <p>This is based on a study of about 100 well-designed websites where I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fHb">
            <p>checked the brightness of containers against the backgrounds.  Make</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zHT">
            <p>outer padding the same or more than inner padding</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Umb">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Jsu">
            <p>In containers, inner padding is the space between elements inside the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hKF">
            <p>container. Outer padding is the space between the elements and the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Q6q">
            <p>edges of the container. This outer padding should be the same or more</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ClA">
            <p>than the inner padding. Elements that are more related should be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4Ru">
            <p>closer together. The elements inside a container are more related to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="6-L">
            <p>each other than they are to the container itself.  Keep body text at</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Lww">
            <p>16px or above</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ffs">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="50G">
            <p>16px is the default text size in most browsers. Text below this size</p>
          </li>
          <li id="s_f">
            <p>gets harder to read, so it’s safest to avoid it for body text. The</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ABy">
            <p>higher you go beyond 16px, the easier the text is to read.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Exu">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="0iE">
            <p>If you are writing code yourself, use whatever equivalent of pixels</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Sc-">
            <p>you prefer.  Use a line length around 70 characters</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Jz2">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="jck">
            <p>It doesn’t matter too much if your line length is 60 or 80 characters,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sYY">
            <p>but go too far either side of that and you might run into subtle</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WHP">
            <p>readability issues.  Make horizontal padding twice the vertical</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xiu">
            <p>padding in buttons</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tY6">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="4G5">
            <p>The standard button pattern is wider than it is tall. If you want</p>
          </li>
          <li id="j0k">
            <p>people to recognise an element as a button, it’s a good idea to follow</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GC0">
            <p>the pattern. In the example below, the padding above and below the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="bAX">
            <p>label is 30px, and the padding to the left and right is 60px.  Use two</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0hg">
            <p>typefaces at most</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B7Q">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_bB">
            <p>A second typeface is an opportunity to reinforce the concept behind a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Jat">
            <p>design. It also helps add some variety to a design. It’s rarely</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5S2">
            <p>necessary to use more than two, and it might make the design feel</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7tl">
            <p>visually confused.  Nest corners properly</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3KS">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Hzs">
            <p>Sometimes you will have two or more rounded corners nested</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Tbm">
            <p>together. If you want them to look right, set the inside corner radius</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dcm">
            <p>to the outside corner radius, minus the distance between the two. In</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ec_">
            <p>the example below the outside radius is 30px, and there is a 20px gap,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mIz">
            <p>so the inside corner radius is 10px.  Don’t put two hard divides next</p>
          </li>
          <li id="J0O">
            <p>to each other</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S0G">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ju-">
            <p>Background transitions, container edges, and dividing lines will</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Gjw">
            <p>create hard visual divides. You should not have two or more hard</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Bhx">
            <p>divides next to each other. You can see this marked in red in the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Bw6">
            <p>example below. More than one hard divide creates visual clutter and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pWQ">
            <p>catches the eye. In the example I have removed the background</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7uS">
            <p>transition so that the hard divide only comes from the container edge.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="DYLz">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="fBk5">
        <p>Emails to academic staff</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="lH5w">
            <p>Dear [Name],</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Wr">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Xq">
            <p>I trust you had a nice Christmas break and New Year.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="biwL">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="mOpI">
            <p>Due to a very unfortunate set of circumstances surrounding bereavement</p>
          </li>
          <li id="AY">
            <p>and some serious ailments, I was rendered unfit to complete your</p>
          </li>
          <li id="yl">
            <p>module [insert module] last year. This was officially approved as</p>
          </li>
          <li id="qQ">
            <p>extenuating cirumstances by the school office.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ZV">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="iD">
            <p>I will now need to resit the entire</p>
          </li>
          <li id="df">
            <p>module including all coursework and examinations.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="I4">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="qc">
            <p>I would be most grateful if you could provide some guidance concerning this.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wg">
            <p>Namely around:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9c">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="lZ">
            <p>-   Coursework timelines and submission dates</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fR">
            <p>-   Exam dates</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mI">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="mE">
            <p>I consider myself a relatively indpendent learner, so I hope that this</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Em">
            <p>re-sitting of course material will cause minimal disruption to you, as</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zk">
            <p>I am conscious of your time.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5sBa">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="FU">
            <p>Wishing you a fine day ahead,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="n9">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Jg">
            <p>Ben</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jK">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="mb">
            <p>Dear Kevin,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wt">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="BR">
            <p>I hope you had a nice break and New Year.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0G">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="0l">
            <p>Unfortunately, I faced some unexpected personal issues and ailments</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jp88">
            <p>that prevented me from completing the Honours Project (SOC10101) last</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Zu">
            <p>year. These issues were recognised as extenuating circumstances by the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="NR">
            <p>school office. As a result, I require a deferral of submission.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="t5">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="lG">
            <p>I would be most grateful if you could provide some guidance on the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="UZ">
            <p>following:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Jt">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="uG">
            <p>-   The new submission date for the Honours Project</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ws">
            <p>-   Any structural or administrative changes that will arise as a result of this circumstance</p>
          </li>
          <li id="iK">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="tJ">
            <p>Best regards,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SicA">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="pu">
            <p>Ben</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nP__">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="rok">
            <p>Dear Kevin,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tL6">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="yl3">
            <p>I hope you had a good break and happy New Year. Unfortunately, I faced</p>
          </li>
          <li id="JOn">
            <p>some unexpected personal issues and ailments that prevented me from</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wtZ">
            <p>completing the Honours Project (SOC10101) last year. This situation</p>
          </li>
          <li id="AYf">
            <p>has been recognised by the school office as extenuating circumstances,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ftW">
            <p>and as a result, I require a deferral for the submission date of the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mt7">
            <p>project.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0eO">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="P1v">
            <p>I would be most grateful if you could help me with the following:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="qzs">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="mnw">
            <p>-   Provide a new submission date for the Honours Project</p>
          </li>
          <li id="DOz">
            <p>-   Inform me about any changes to the structure or administration of the project as a result of this situation</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jiF">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="N-0">
            <p>Best regards,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="s1u">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Wck">
            <p>Ben</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="1Qzj">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="yK8e">
        <p>Arina</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="yTw1">
            <p>Here I will attempt to outline my conundrums and concerns:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YaTg">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="43">
            <p>I do not intend, by discussing this with you, to procure a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Cw">
            <p>relationship scorecard, or anything of that nature, and so on.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ng">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="kA">
            <p>What I intend to do, is outline my most pressing concerns and worries</p>
          </li>
          <li id="r7">
            <p>in hopes that we may resovle them together.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2_">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="eE">
            <p>Inevitably you will take these points personally, as they do concern</p>
          </li>
          <li id="i0">
            <p>you.  However, they are not intended as attacks of character or your</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wS">
            <p>way of living, they are simply my miniumum and base conditions for a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="EG">
            <p>healthy relationship.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-W">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="RC">
            <p>I. The most pressing issue (and there is no roundabout or</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oB">
            <p>soft delivery for this) relates to accountability and the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="HO">
            <p>dissenemation of tasks.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="6M">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="D_">
            <p>I.I. It is *crucial* that you find employment. This</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ri">
            <p>employment should cover all your personal costs outside of household</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SB">
            <p>bills (bar council tax, as I think you should pay this once your</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cr">
            <p>student exemption expires, and any payments for any time</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-L">
            <p>inbetween.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="1p">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="SGWC">
            <p>I.II. Vincent. The very concept of joint and share ownership</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vJ">
            <p>neccessitates distributed accountability. This idea transcends age,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="84">
            <p>career, politics, culture. It is important that you take equal</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Nk">
            <p>responsbility for Vincent. This includes:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="RY">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="0N">
            <p>-   Taking Vincent to the vet when required</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Vj">
            <p>-   Cleaning Vincent's toilet, when required (this should now be done</p>
            <ul>
              <li id="9u">
                <p>once per day by simply scooping poos into the bin).</p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="dI">
            <p>-   Help in training Vincent and or preventing Vincent from damaging</p>
            <ul>
              <li id="_t">
                <p>properties</p>
              </li>
              <li id="-2">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="th">
            <p>I propose we alternate the responsibility of the above three points.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9l">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="eo-g">
            <p>II. We work as a team, especially when it comes to fair notice. It is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="07">
            <p>more than reasonable for you to want to visit and/or see friends and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fP">
            <p>even stay at their homes.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vd">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="pU">
            <p>Likewise, it is just as reasonable for me to have apt written</p>
          </li>
          <li id="TC">
            <p>notice. I appreciate that I sometimes forget, but it is also not my</p>
          </li>
          <li id="G5">
            <p>responsibility to note and track every intricacy of your life, and to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="g6">
            <p>do so would be abnormal.  This should now be in the form of a joint</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tg">
            <p>diary or calendar. This can be some synced calendar that we both use</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5_">
            <p>to plan what happens and when. Of course there will be exemptions, and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="kt">
            <p>naturally so, but I feel this is a very important point to make.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wX">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="M3_9">
            <p>III. Cleaning of the household. I feel I have made significant efforts</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ss">
            <p>to clean the household and maintain my share of the house work in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Db">
            <p>recent days. I would very much like if this could be reciprocated on</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wV">
            <p>your end (specifically regarding the area close to the mirror, above</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Fd">
            <p>your wardrobe and in and around the bed).</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Wb">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="EX">
            <p>IIII. Ultimate and uncontested freedom of travel. I would like to be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ad">
            <p>able to travel freely, to explore other cultures, and not feel any</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2T">
            <p>burden for making financial efforts to do (e.g. saving). Whilst I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="bL">
            <p>appreciate the importance of travelling together, and we should do so,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="46">
            <p>I also want to travel alone and hope that this will be respected.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="uX">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="sw">
            <p>V. Active involvement in each-others social events. I would like to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YY">
            <p>socialise more often and have this reciprocated. I want to make effort</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5N">
            <p>this year to engage more with my friends and office, but would also</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Oq">
            <p>like to meet more of your friends and chat with them.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="V2">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="bZ">
            <p>VI. I would really appreciate your help in searching for new flats or</p>
          </li>
          <li id="12">
            <p>places to live. I can help you to understand what we are looking for</p>
          </li>
          <li id="bW">
            <p>(e.g. long-term lettings, not short-term), acceptable deposits,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="yX">
            <p>acceptable notice periods, acceptable internet speeds, etc. I would</p>
          </li>
          <li id="XI">
            <p>also greatly appreciate your understanding that you may not be able to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fj">
            <p>attend all viewings personally due to the *extremely* competitive nature</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OX">
            <p>of the current market and the fact that viewing dates and times will</p>
          </li>
          <li id="kO">
            <p>likely clash with your course. I'd appreciate if you do not hold this</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Rk">
            <p>fact against me, as I am now keen to move anywhere as soon as</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Wv">
            <p>possible, even if the property quality is only a little better, I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9b">
            <p>desperately need a new scene.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="u3h">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="1b1">
        <p>Writing about writing</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="Va">
            <p>It seems to me that writing is a therapeutic endeavour.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5Z">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ae">
            <p>With writing we can take a step back to analyse our thoughts and our thought processes.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Qp">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="LP">
            <p>It is meta-thinking.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4MX-">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="PC">
            <p>This form of private journal is very helpful, I believe.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="kYG">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="7Am">
        <p>Photographs of Agony</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="hjp">
            <p>The possible contradictions of the war photograph now become</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3bD">
            <p>apparent. It is generally assumed that its purpose is to awaken</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Q8">
            <p>concern. The most extreme examples - as in most of McCullin's work -</p>
          </li>
          <li id="DM">
            <p>show moments of agony in order to exort the maximum concern. Such</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WM">
            <p>moments, whether photographed or not, are discontinuous with all other</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0n">
            <p>moments. They exist by themselves. But the reader who has been</p>
          </li>
          <li id="93">
            <p>arrested by the photograph may tend to feel this discontinuity as his</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vl">
            <p>own personal moral inadeuqecy. *And as soon as this happens even his*</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lj">
            <p>*sense of shock is dispersed*: his own moral inadequacy as being only</p>
          </li>
          <li id="q4">
            <p>too familiar, or else he thinks of performing a kind of penance - of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="kf">
            <p>which the purest example would be to make a contribution to Oxfam or</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vp">
            <p>Unicef. In both cases, the issue of the war which has caused that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_BS">
            <p>moment is effectively depoliticised. The picture becomes evidence of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KE">
            <p>the gerneal human condition. It accueses nobody and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2a">
            <p>everybody. Confrontation with a photographed moment of agony can mask</p>
          </li>
          <li id="A7">
            <p>a far more extensive and urgent confrontation. Usually the wars which</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Pk">
            <p>we are shown are being fought directlly or indirectly in 'our'</p>
          </li>
          <li id="y5">
            <p>name. What we are sshown horrifies us. The next step should be for us</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wJ">
            <p>to confront our own lack of political freedom. In the political</p>
          </li>
          <li id="rj">
            <p>systems as they exist, we have no legal opportunity of effectively</p>
          </li>
          <li id="6q">
            <p>influencing the conduct of wars waged in our name. To realise this and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B6">
            <p>to act accordingly is the only effective way of responding to what the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="t0">
            <p>photograph shows. Yet the double violence of the photographed moment</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8C">
            <p>actually works against this realisation. That is why they can be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Od">
            <p>published with impunity.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="wF8">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="tGg">
        <p>Invisible Cities</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="CBR">
            <p>"You reach a moment in life when, among the people you have known, the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ff">
            <p>dead outnumber the living. And the mind refuses to accept more faces,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="PZ">
            <p>more expressions: on every new face you encounter, it prints the old</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mb">
            <p>forms, for each one it finds the most suitable mask."</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="4-C">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="aP7">
        <p>Paper on boredom</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="Tar">
            <p>Heidegger’s (1929/30) lectures on The Fundamental Concepts of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="j7">
            <p>Metaphysics</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dB">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="gu">
            <p>Heidegger saw that through profound boredom, we can see the world</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tW">
            <p>anew, question what makes life meaningful to us, and connect these</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Z-">
            <p>interests to a me</p>
          </li>
          <li id="FW">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_J">
            <p>As Heidegger (1995: 80) notes, boredom bears ‘an almost obvious</p>
          </li>
          <li id="iU">
            <p>relation to time, a way in which we stand with respect to time, a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aa">
            <p>feeling of time’.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wP">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Qi">
            <p>Murphy, S., Hill, T., McDonagh, P., &amp; Flaherty, A. (2022). Mundane</p>
          </li>
          <li id="VX">
            <p>emotions: Losing yourself in boredom, time and technology. Marketing</p>
          </li>
          <li id="yB">
            <p>Theory, 0(0). &lt;https://doi.org/10.1177/14705931221138617&gt;</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="3h2">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="1JQ">
        <p>Conversion between reader and writer</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="Tfi">
            <p>"In a conversation that a reader has with a book in the privacy of his</p>
          </li>
          <li id="JA">
            <p>own study, there is nothing to prevent the reader from seeming to win</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GS">
            <p>the argument. He can dominate the situation. The author is not there</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mx">
            <p>to defend himself. If all he wants is the empty satisfaction of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3k">
            <p>seeming to show the author up, the reader can get it readily. He</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GN">
            <p>scarecly has to read the book through to get it. Glancing at the first</p>
          </li>
          <li id="X3">
            <p>few pages will suffice. But if he realises that the only profit in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oV">
            <p>conversation, with living or deadteachers, is what one can learn from</p>
          </li>
          <li id="U3">
            <p>them, if he realises that you win only by gaining knowledge, not by</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nT">
            <p>knocking theirother fellow down, he may see the futility of mere</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2j">
            <p>contentiousness."</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lX">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Lf">
            <p>Mortimer J. Adler &amp;#x2013; How to Read a Book: The Classic Guide to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Lx">
            <p>Intelligent Reading</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="sVo">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="6iG">
        <p>Weaponising the admission of a mistake</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="GfB">
            <p>I think there is a tendency to weaponise another's mistake.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="64">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="hnW">
            <p>If someone admits to being mistaken, or for holding a compromised</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WP">
            <p>viewpoint, and then later admits to doing so, such an admission should</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9W">
            <p>not be held against them in future.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="v_">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="6q8">
            <p>This is because it risks spawning a viscious and self-perpetuating</p>
          </li>
          <li id="c1">
            <p>loop, whereby the instigator of the admission becomes less likely to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9X">
            <p>concede in future arguments by default because it might be held</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mg">
            <p>against them for doing so.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ve">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="3p">
            <p>This can be circumvented easily via avoidance of focus on the current</p>
          </li>
          <li id="1cs">
            <p>argument. Avoid drawing attention to any past debates where either</p>
          </li>
          <li id="94v">
            <p>party was wrong or right. i.e. avoid the use of "but you said X and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="im">
            <p>the outcome was Y, I told you so."</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="4iD">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="yp6">
        <p>Phoenix applications are one giant function </p>
        <ul>
          <li id="gxL">
            <p>I think this aligns with the *functional* heart and nature of Elixir</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_U">
            <p>programs. The Phoenix framework is essentially one giant function that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WH">
            <p>starts at `%Plug.Conn{}` and is then manipulated by additional plugs.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B3">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Vu">
            <p>Every plug that comes into contact with this initial "connection"</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mz">
            <p>plug, returns it in some updated state. It is a really nice pipeline</p>
          </li>
          <li id="CF">
            <p>paradigm.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="it">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ZA">
            <p>Another way to think about this is a *production line* in a factory. The</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3f">
            <p>request works its way down the conveyor belt and is modified along the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9x">
            <p>way to result in some arbitrary response (that differs from the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="x5">
            <p>request in some way).</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Tf">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="HI">
            <p>The example given in the book on LiveView is the following:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3r">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="aX">
                <p>connection_from_request</p>
                <ul>
                  <li id="3_">
                    <p>|&gt; endpoint</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="w5">
                    <p>|&gt; router</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="Gi">
                    <p>|&gt; custom_application</p>
                  </li>
                  <li id="rD">
                    <p/>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Dk">
            <p>Associated reading: [Anatomy of a Phoenix app](20221218T174402--anatomy-of-a-phoenix-app.md), [Notes on Programming</p>
          </li>
          <li id="L3">
            <p>Phoenix LiveView](20221218T161250--notes-on-programming-phoenix-liveview.md)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="8sw">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="_aF">
            <p>The interesting thing about this is you can use the game "Factorio" as</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Er4">
            <p>an almost 1-1 mapping of the system.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oRB">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="sx0">
            <p>This is how you know that Phoenix is a well-designed framework.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ZiT">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="sB3">
            <p>Conveyor belts = pipeline</p>
          </li>
          <li id="C36">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="RS3">
            <p>Plugs = assemblers or assembly machines</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2vN">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="cyL">
            <p>Router = some advance splitter or load balancer</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="3dZ">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="FkI">
        <p>Anatomy of a phoenix app</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="cdd">
            <p># Table of Contents</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Z1">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="EE">
            <p>1.  [Changesets](#org6b655e5)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cI">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ht">
            <p>Phoenix apps foster a very idiomatic and pragmatic layout.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ZT">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="6g">
            <p>All assets required for the project are stored in an `assets` directory.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zx">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="gd">
            <p>Any web-based code is stored inside `lib/proj_web` .</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jo">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="XS">
            <p>All core business logic and backend code is housed inside `lib/proj`.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="isD">
            <p>(where `proj` is the name of the project)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="DD">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="qa">
            <p>Interestingly, the `context` is referred to as the `api` for the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="l1">
            <p>application. I'm not entirely sure how this analogy fits together just</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3D">
            <p>yet.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hD">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="hM">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="uh">
            <p>&lt;a id="org6b655e5"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S2">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="UF">
            <p># Changesets</p>
          </li>
          <li id="By">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Ox">
            <p>Inside a changeset, the use of `cast` is effectively a filter for fields.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oM">
            <p>Only fields included in the `cast` are allowed, e.g.:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WT">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="wR">
                <p>|&gt; cast(attrs, [:name])</p>
              </li>
              <li id="L_">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="VD">
            <p>Only the `:name` attribute is accepted by the above cahngeset.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Cd">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="tH">
            <p>Cast also converts the attributes into the `type` that is expected by</p>
          </li>
          <li id="gp">
            <p>the schema.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zB">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="jn">
            <p>`push_redirect` is used as a server-side push (I believe this to be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Fi">
            <p>somewhat equivalent to Next. `live_redirect` is the client-side version</p>
          </li>
          <li id="O4">
            <p>of this function.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="qP">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="bR">
            <p>I do wonder what the logic behind this naming is?</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Pe">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Ts">
            <p>Surely `server_redirect` and `client_redirect` are preferable?</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oW4">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="KA">
            <p>It is possible to include references in the generation step:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="wC">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="k5">
                <p>mix phx.gen.context Survey Demographic demographics gender:string \</p>
              </li>
              <li id="uC">
                <p>year_of_birth:integer user_id:references:users:unique</p>
              </li>
              <li id="m7">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Sf">
            <p>And similarly with:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="AW">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="-D">
                <p>mix phx.gen.context Survey Rating ratings stars:integer \</p>
              </li>
              <li id="vI">
                <p>user_id:references:users product_id:references:products</p>
              </li>
              <li id="R6">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Dw">
            <p>&gt; Ecto query composition, as you already know, is certain and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Nj">
            <p>&gt; predictable. It belongs in your application’s core.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="bt">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="0g">
            <p>&gt; Remember, Ecto is explicit. If you want it to load relationships, you</p>
          </li>
          <li id="IC">
            <p>&gt; need to ask for them.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="MN">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="qd">
            <p>&gt; A function component is a function that takes in an assigns argument</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nh">
            <p>&gt; and returns a HEEx template</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="8s4">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="rZA">
        <p>Tailwind apply directive</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="1g">
            <p>Today I've learnt about the Tailwind @apply directive. This is pretty</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zL">
            <p>helpful for styling HTML elements in a global .css file, e.g.: see the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Xl">
            <p>below:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="83A">
            <p/>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="R-S">
        <p>Notes on Phoenix LiveView</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="8zJ">
            <p># The basic architecture</p>
          </li>
          <li id="z9">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="fV">
            <p>My understanding is that the base architecture of a LiveView app is as</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_l">
            <p>follows (3-layer based):</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pZ">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="7i">
            <p>-   Frontend code (essentially markdown files with LiveView sprinkled in?)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9p">
            <p>-   Context (boundary layer). This seems to be described almost like a</p>
            <ul>
              <li id="5q">
                <p>middleware. It protects the "core" schema layer from the frontend by</p>
              </li>
              <li id="y2">
                <p>enforicing sanitisation (in the form of what is called</p>
              </li>
              <li id="Tg">
                <p>"changesets").</p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Fe">
            <p>-   Core: the core interfaces with the database. It includes the data</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="BXr">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="lYT">
        <p>Phoenix verified routes</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="RG">
            <p>It is possible to use verified routes in Phoenix by appending a tilde</p>
          </li>
          <li id="41">
            <p>(~p) to them, e.g. I'm not 100% sure how this works yet but it seems</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xB">
            <p>quite useful.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B7">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="hj">
            <p>[See here](https://github.com/phoenixframework/phoenix/blob/master/guides/routing.md#verified-routes)</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="bVt">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="YR1">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="Ii3">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="Tk3">
        <p>Bill’s response to the parallel self</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="Zlq">
            <p>Bill's response:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="J8">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="i2">
            <p>Ben, Let me start with a caution. The areas of self and person address</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ya">
            <p>the fundamentals of human existence. Prolonged exposure, study, in</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fk">
            <p>areas such as those has been known to cause depression. My caution is</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nl">
            <p>if you want to continue studying philosophy, cultivate a detached</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Z8">
            <p>persona to do it, an academic approach. To find personal issues worth</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YQ">
            <p>study is a valid approach but the exercise needs to maintain</p>
          </li>
          <li id="M2">
            <p>distance. Now to your conundrum:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="14">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="KU">
            <p>1.  Current state: unproductive and ungrateful</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ir">
            <p>2.  Intermediary state: do the thing (i.e. go to the office)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ei">
            <p>3.  Future state: productive and grateful</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Bg">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="T8">
            <p>Are these three statements (as propositions) entirely accurate?  Point</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cR">
            <p>1 seems to imply they are not. I perceive logical inexactitude partly</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SG">
            <p>due to language limitation/selection and partly due to mixing the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ua_">
            <p>objective with the subjective.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sb-">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="aAP">
            <p>You place what I will call Self 1 (S1) in a defined state. A state</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BE5">
            <p>that is currently held, by S1, to be less than ideal. Is the word</p>
          </li>
          <li id="LZF">
            <p>‘unproductive’, in this case, a comparative? Compared to who, what? If</p>
          </li>
          <li id="r8N">
            <p>the comparator is external we would have one argument if the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SfG">
            <p>comparator is internal it would be an entirely different debate.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0DY">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="vMw">
            <p>If, as I suspect, it is internal then who is making the comparison? As</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3eR">
            <p>the future self does not yet exist it must be S1. I would argue that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aKR">
            <p>progress in any situation can only be achieved at the cost of changing</p>
          </li>
          <li id="eDe">
            <p>what a past self (S1x) put in place. At the time that S1x put that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="TZ6">
            <p>construction in place was it done with intellectual integrity ie the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Jhg">
            <p>best that could be achieved with the available resources? Resources</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GD8">
            <p>would include personal capabilities, temporal limitations, external</p>
          </li>
          <li id="q9h">
            <p>impositions and materials available.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lFH">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="j0N">
            <p>Assume S1x was productive within the limits imposed by the resources</p>
          </li>
          <li id="gRi">
            <p>at the time. Since the S1 person is the derivative of S1x (he cannot</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lBY">
            <p>be derived from any other person) it must argue that S1x passed to S1</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9EQ">
            <p>a situation that S1x expected S1 to view with scepticism. This is what</p>
          </li>
          <li id="CUw">
            <p>S1x did to bring about the existing situation by changing what went</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Upd">
            <p>before (from an even earlier S1 iteration) so he also recognised the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tb9">
            <p>need for scepticism.  Intellectually speaking S1 can only fail, be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KNj">
            <p>unproductive, if he knowingly fails to apply this imperative to the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Oog">
            <p>work of S1x. Imperfection is the natural state of humans. Even knowing</p>
          </li>
          <li id="pLg">
            <p>this the perpetual pursuit of perfection is what brought us to where</p>
          </li>
          <li id="gLA">
            <p>we are. It is what we are, what we do. It is, to take a Darwinian</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Prf">
            <p>view, inherent to the function of being human.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BQh">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="xGl">
            <p>Failure (be it complete or partial) is not a negative, the fear of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S0X">
            <p>failure is. Advance is the phoenix that rises from failure’s ashes. It</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4HW">
            <p>drives change, resolve, exploration but only with the honesty to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2PS">
            <p>accept personal imperfection. The future S1 (S1f) will be the amalgam</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0Dt">
            <p>of all prior S1x’s and S1. S1f holds potential. Einstein knew this. He</p>
          </li>
          <li id="3i-">
            <p>saw flaws in General Relativity and said of Quantum Mechanics it was</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xaS">
            <p>“spooky action at a distance”, he expected holes to be made apparent</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KXl">
            <p>in his magnus opus. It was not a failure since his goal was not to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Mj7">
            <p>explain ‘everything’ but to make strides toward that goal.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="F03">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="AyN">
            <p>Reinhold Niebuhr, a theologian and ethicist considered this seeming</p>
          </li>
          <li id="I5V">
            <p>contradiction and produced the ‘Serenity Prayer’.  “Lord, grant me the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="RP1">
            <p>strength to accept the things I cannot change,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="B30">
            <p>the courage to change</p>
          </li>
          <li id="guG">
            <p>the things I can,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="R_2">
            <p>and the wisdom to know the difference.” As an</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2vG">
            <p>atheist I cannot accept the role of a deity however the main points</p>
          </li>
          <li id="PvE">
            <p>recognise the ‘imperfection’ of life and the nature of being human -</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Yfx">
            <p>particularly the last line.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="clh">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="GxC">
            <p>For these and other reasons I would also challenge the inclusion of</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Rup">
            <p>the word ‘ungrateful’ and I would offer instead frustrated.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="BZZ">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="VYa">
            <p>As to how you proceed, you have a choice but I would suggest some</p>
          </li>
          <li id="43J">
            <p>resolution is necessary. Some of that is a definition of self (which I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="yQe">
            <p>would suggest you accept will be flawed). We are all prototypes of a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S0O">
            <p>future self, constantly evolving, reacting, revising. The external</p>
          </li>
          <li id="g3k">
            <p>world will play a part. Example; we once accepted slavery. It was</p>
          </li>
          <li id="K63">
            <p>politically acceptable, economically beneficial and yet wholly</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Ut9">
            <p>immoral. Those thinkers who tore down the practise were anathema to a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="sc1">
            <p>vast part of established orthodoxy. The external forces ranged against</p>
          </li>
          <li id="G1x">
            <p>the reformers were immense. It caused changes in their behaviour</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7cr">
            <p>(their person changed) which in turn caused a change in the persons</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ewi">
            <p>around them.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oPL">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="yRP">
            <p>You may be frustrated with yourself. Frustration is a portmanteau</p>
          </li>
          <li id="xst">
            <p>term. Analyse it. What is wrong? The speed of progress toward a goal?</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vvt">
            <p>The scope of the goal? The personal resources you can bring to bear?</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SNm">
            <p>These relate to your point one, current state. Without some resolution</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WE-">
            <p>your second point, the intermediary is always going to be</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zqm">
            <p>suspect. When setting point 2 the What to do question is surpassed by</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OmM">
            <p>the Why. Why are you going to the office? There are many answers none</p>
          </li>
          <li id="lg5">
            <p>wholly correct or wholly wrong. You could answer ‘to earn some money’</p>
          </li>
          <li id="opK">
            <p>which would be correct but probably not complete. To ‘make something</p>
          </li>
          <li id="P-i">
            <p>better’? Again correct but again incomplete. We should also recognise</p>
          </li>
          <li id="2l5">
            <p>those selfish drivers like ‘to be recognised as better than what went</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0QY">
            <p>before’ again incomplete</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OX5">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="U_-">
            <p>At the risk of stating the bleedin’ obvious I am older than you so my</p>
          </li>
          <li id="hap">
            <p>perspectives are different. I can look back over 70 years and my S1</p>
          </li>
          <li id="uIA">
            <p>can look at the decisions my S1x took and form a judgement based on</p>
          </li>
          <li id="WSO">
            <p>the attitudes, beliefs of my current self. Some of those will return a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0tS">
            <p>regret. I will give an example, a serious one. I have to request that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tNf">
            <p>you treat what follows with discretion.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KqK">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="iYI">
            <p>As an 18 year old I met a woman, I Iiked her. After a few dates she</p>
          </li>
          <li id="kBt">
            <p>told me she had a 3month old baby I chose to continue the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="7o2">
            <p>relationship. After a year or so I was faced with a decision. The baby</p>
          </li>
          <li id="A_h">
            <p>was beginning to form views of the world, develop a personality,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ADl">
            <p>define self and relationships toward those in her orbit including</p>
          </li>
          <li id="EqZ">
            <p>me. Social pressures (those that existed then but have changed now)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="aGk">
            <p>leaned towards marriage. My choices appeared to me to be binary, stay</p>
          </li>
          <li id="MWu">
            <p>or go. I chose to stay with a consequence of marriage. It was an error</p>
          </li>
          <li id="LN1">
            <p>because I had failed to take the need for deep emotional attachment</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fi6">
            <p>into account and was responding, largely, to external pressures.. I</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jrd">
            <p>felt that I was doing the ‘right’ thing for the ‘right’ reasons,</p>
          </li>
          <li id="RXo">
            <p>consideration of the child. Twenty years down the line everything fell</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YwJ">
            <p>apart and damaged all parties involved.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="-ZS">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="VGp">
            <p>With the benefit of hindsight I would claim I hold no fault for my</p>
          </li>
          <li id="GbV">
            <p>original decisions beyond the deeply regretted failure to adequately</p>
          </li>
          <li id="N2I">
            <p>account for the importance of emotional attachment. I knew I had</p>
          </li>
          <li id="0G2">
            <p>doubts but lacked the honesty and courage to address them. Those are</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KBb">
            <p>personal failings I can address now. Had I done so then I would have</p>
          </li>
          <li id="QpF">
            <p>caused sadness, temporary hopefully, but I would have avoided the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Zpm">
            <p>permanent and extensive damage in later years. Sometimes there is no</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oD3">
            <p>happy outcome. The wisdom comes later. The failure (mine) is converted</p>
          </li>
          <li id="KtZ">
            <p>from negative to positive if I can show the error in my thinking and</p>
          </li>
          <li id="vnl">
            <p>pass that knowledge (flawed as it will be) to others before they find</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Z6s">
            <p>themselves making a similar critical decision. To do so requires that</p>
          </li>
          <li id="nBz">
            <p>I re-examine my actions on a regular basis and change as required. If</p>
          </li>
          <li id="ha7">
            <p>I am lucky, and chance is a factor in human thinking, I help them to</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5iZ">
            <p>understand a situation without the need to experience it. Their ‘self’</p>
          </li>
          <li id="zCY">
            <p>will have changed through an agency over which they had no</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5ip">
            <p>control.They will still hold an imperfect paradigm but it will be just</p>
          </li>
          <li id="SO7">
            <p>a little less imperfect. They will still be ‘I’ but not the ‘me’ they</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Cw1">
            <p>were before. They will be one of the infinite versions of S1f that had</p>
          </li>
          <li id="842">
            <p>awaited realisation as S1 when the future became now.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="C5z">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="Ppx">
            <p>I do hope this helps rather than confuses. I have studied ‘self’ on</p>
          </li>
          <li id="oLm">
            <p>the MA course. Whilst we all believe we know ourselves when confronted</p>
          </li>
          <li id="jqV">
            <p>with a demand for the evidence we find it to be nebulous, shifting</p>
          </li>
          <li id="S0a">
            <p>sands in the winds of circumstance. That actually isn’t a bad</p>
          </li>
          <li id="dZ3">
            <p>analogy. The Sahara exists it can be seen, touched, walked</p>
          </li>
          <li id="cj4">
            <p>across. Answering questions as to exactly where it is, where the dunes</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OYp">
            <p>are now and what will be the situation in a century, an hour or even a</p>
          </li>
          <li id="9ZS">
            <p>second from now is problematical. It will still be there, still be the</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Si5">
            <p>Sahara but it will, as with humans, defy permanent and complete</p>
          </li>
          <li id="fgo">
            <p>definition.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="k7A">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="2SM">
        <p>Remove top tabs on Firefox</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="04h">
            <p>This is a good modification if you are using [Tree Style Tabs Extension](https://github.com/piroor/treestyletab).</p>
          </li>
          <li id="4y">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="2E">
            <p>To hide the native tabs, you'll have to add a new file called userChrome.css and the css property visibility: collapse.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="mq">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="a7">
            <p>To do this, in Firefox click on Click on Menu -&gt; Help -&gt; Troubleshooting Information or navigate to about:support in the address bar.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="YE">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="yk">
            <p>Under the Application Basics section, there will be a section called Profile Directory with a button to Open Directory.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="XT">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="wL">
            <p>In the Profile Directory create a new folder called chrome. In the chrome folder create or edit the file userChrome.css if it already exists.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="tM">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="ti">
            <p>The contents of userChrome.css should be the following.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Kl">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="ni">
                <p>/* hides the native tabs */</p>
              </li>
              <li id="nP">
                <p>#TabsToolbar {</p>
              </li>
              <li id="q9">
                <p>visibility: collapse;</p>
              </li>
              <li id="85">
                <p>}</p>
              </li>
              <li id="Da">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Za">
            <p>Some optional further modifications to put in userChrome.css are:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="Xn">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="-p">
                <p>/* hides the title bar */</p>
              </li>
              <li id="YT">
                <p>#titlebar {</p>
              </li>
              <li id="-8">
                <p>visibility: collapse;</p>
              </li>
              <li id="Kw">
                <p>}</p>
              </li>
              <li id="NX">
                <p/>
              </li>
              <li id="kd">
                <p>/* hides the sidebar */</p>
              </li>
              <li id="6C">
                <p>#sidebar-header {</p>
              </li>
              <li id="CO">
                <p>visibility: collapse !important;</p>
              </li>
              <li id="_4">
                <p>}</p>
              </li>
              <li id="D6">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="Kg">
            <p>[Firefix open "look up" in new tab](20221219T230229--firefix-open-loop-up-in-new-tab.md)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="OQa">
            <p>[New workflow weekly](20230702T162402--new-workflow-weekly.md)</p>
          </li>
          <li id="os">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="-h">
            <p>IMPORTANT:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="_F">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="zJ">
            <p>Make sure to modify the following inside about:config:</p>
          </li>
          <li id="5u">
            <p/>
            <ul>
              <li id="0D">
                <p>toolkit.legacyUserProfileCustomizations.stylesheets = true</p>
              </li>
              <li id="aI">
                <p/>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li id="2r">
            <p>To equal true, otherwise the above will not take effect.</p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="hnf">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="sP">
        <p>Something went really wrong yesterday. I can’t pinpoint why I am acting in this way. It doesn’t make any sense. It’s almost as though I’ve stopped caring about other people which is really terrifying.</p>
      </li>
      <li id="RK">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="pN7">
        <p>I’m fallling in love with this new font. I’ve been using Titilium Web, which is the font that Factorio uses in-game and honestly it feels great. I’m really enjoying using it. It works perfectly in combination with the Bike editor. I wish I could use it as my Apple font. </p>
      </li>
      <li id="DBB">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="AECD_ZLDaw3kmF8KOSUgn" data-created="2025-12-24T07:49:49Z" data-modified="2025-12-24T07:49:55Z">
        <p>Feelings 24 Dec 24</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="fpa3Vt9vMaRSW8whxbESj" data-created="2025-12-24T07:49:55Z" data-modified="2025-12-24T09:54:19Z">
            <p>I need to become more reliable. Why am I acting so childish recently? I really don’t like it. I need to be dependable, reliable, etc. There would be no difference between me and my Dad if I continue to act in this way. This is exactly what he did and I should avoid it if I can. It’s not productive. </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li id="aPs">
        <p/>
      </li>
      <li id="-pp">
        <p>Dahee</p>
        <ul>
          <li id="RH">
            <p>23/24 Nov 2025 meeting next to Han river.</p>
          </li>
          <li id="MBQ">
            <p/>
          </li>
          <li id="8H">
